                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 32. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>As <orig>Corall</orig> <orig>growes</orig> under water, and is hardened by the <orig>aire</orig>,
                        <lb/><orig>Soe</orig> <orig>allso</orig> is the Stone.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 32.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>In the Sicilian waves a Sea=plant <orig>growes</orig>,</l>
                        <l>Shooting forth many moist and <choice><orig>plyant</orig><reg>pliant</reg></choice> <choice><orig>boughes</orig><reg>boughs</reg></choice>:</l>
                        <l><orig>Corall</orig> it is by name; whose nature's such,</l>
                        <l>That, if exposed to <choice><orig>th'</orig><reg>the</reg></choice> <orig>aire</orig>, it alters much,</l>
                        <l><del>And</del>A blood red <choice><orig>rocke</orig><reg>rock</reg></choice> becoming: which alone</l>
                        <l>Exactly <orig>repr√¶sents</orig> the <orig>Sophicke</orig> stone.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="102"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 32.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>The Philosophers call their Stone vegetable, because it vegetates, <orig>growes</orig>,<pc>-</pc><milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>is <choice><orig>increasd</orig><reg>increased</reg></choice> and <choice><orig>multipld</orig><reg>multiplied</reg></choice> as a plant: which indeed to the ignorant seems
                        <lb/>strange and contrary to truth; it being manifest that stones <orig>doe</orig> neither
                        <lb/>vegetate, nor grow after this manner, nor any thing at all relate to<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>liquable <orig>metalls</orig>: but they are deceived in their judgment: for that which
                        <lb/>is <orig>unknowne</orig> to them they suppose is not in rerum natura, measuring
                        <lb/>the immensity of the universe by their capacity: For who could ever
                        <lb/>have <orig>beleived</orig> that a stone should grow under water, or a plant there ge
                        <lb break="no"/>nerated become a stone, if experience together with the credible <choice><orig>testimo
                        <lb break="no"/>nyes</orig><reg>testimonies</reg></choice> of writes had not <choice><orig>confirmd</orig><reg>confirmed</reg></choice> it? where is that <choice><orig>petrefying</orig><reg>petrifying</reg></choice>, where<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>that tinging virtue, which <choice><orig>hardeneth</orig><reg>hardens</reg></choice> and <choice><orig>tingeth</orig><reg>tinges</reg></choice> <orig>Corall</orig>, whether in the
                        <lb/>water, or in the <orig>aire</orig>, or in the earth? <orig>wee</orig> may reasonably <orig>beleive</orig> it
                        <lb/>to be, as they <orig>affirme</orig>, a soft and flexible plant, whilst it is under wa
                        <lb break="no"/>ter, yet of a very <choice><orig>terrestriall</orig><reg>terrestrial</reg></choice> nature, which, when it is cut of and exposed
                        <lb/>to the cold winds, becomes hard, and acquires a stony frangibility, the
                        <lb/><orig>watry</orig> parts abounding being <choice><orig>dryed</orig><reg>dried</reg></choice> up by the cold and dry <orig>aire</orig> (for these
                        <lb/>North winds blowing <orig>doe</orig> introduce siccity) and the <orig>terrestriall</orig> body<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>remaining congealed with cold and siccity <subst><del>by</del><add>being</add></subst> the <orig>qualityes</orig> of the earth:
                        <lb/>for constriction <choice><orig>appertaines</orig><reg>appertains</reg></choice> to the earth alone, not to the water, nor <orig>aire</orig>,
                        <lb/>as to the proper and genuine virtues of either. Besides the sea in other
                        <lb/>places <orig>yeilds</orig> three <orig>medicinall</orig> stones deduced partly from the vegetable
                        <lb/>kind, partly from the <orig>animall</orig>, or rather partly from the secrets of na
                        <lb break="no"/>ture; as Pearls, <orig>Ambar</orig>, and <choice><orig>Ambar=grise</orig><reg>Ambar=grise</reg></choice>: the production of Pearls,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and the way of taking them have been <orig>knowne</orig> to us, but not of the
                        <lb/>rest: <orig>Ambar</orig> is found and gathered on the Sea coasts of Sudavia, on the
                        <lb/><orig>shoars</orig>, after a most vehement South or westerly wind, which without
                        <lb/>doubt <orig>boyles</orig> out of the veins of the earth into the Sea, or is <choice><orig>washd</orig><reg>washed</reg></choice><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>out by the water, and driven by the waves to the <orig>shoars</orig>: For <orig>wee</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>have seen some veins of iron and Silver swimming with the <orig>Ambar</orig>,
                        <lb/>which could not be done but in the earth. But as to <add>the</add> <orig>flyes</orig>, <orig>gnatts</orig>,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Spiders, <choice><orig>Butterflyes</orig><reg>Butterflies</reg></choice>, <choice><orig>froggs</orig><reg>frogs</reg></choice>, Serpents which are seen in some <choice><orig>peices</orig><reg>pieces</reg></choice> (as
                        <lb/><orig>wee</orig> have had 120 beads turned out of <orig>Ambar</orig>, which did every one
                        <lb/><orig>containe</orig> some <orig>flyes</orig>, <orig>gnatts</orig>, Spiders, <choice><orig>butterflyes</orig><reg>butterflies</reg></choice>, and one particle nine,
                        <lb/>not without a singular miracle of nature) that happens by the influ
                        <lb break="no"/>ence and imagination of the heaven; as <orig>wee</orig> have <orig>elswhere</orig> demon
                        <lb break="no"/>strated. That <choice><orig>Ambar=grise</orig><reg>Amber=grise</reg></choice> is found after the same manner on the
                        <lb/><orig>Shoars</orig> of the east and west <choice><orig>Indyes</orig><reg>Indies</reg></choice>, cannot be <choice><orig>denyd</orig><reg>denied</reg></choice>, and though<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>some declare it to be the juice or <orig>gumme</orig> of trees, as the <orig>Ambar</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>aforesayd</orig>, yet they that conceive it to proceed out of veins of the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>earth <orig>doe</orig> judge more probably: For <choice><orig>fruitfull</orig><reg>fruitful</reg></choice> trees of <orig>Ambar</orig> have
                        <lb/>been in <orig>noe</orig> place seen, which notwithstanding, if there be, <orig>doe</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>most certainly grow out of the water in the open <orig>aire</orig>: <orig>Wee</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="103"/><fw>Discourse 32.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>therefore ascribe both sorts of <orig>Ambar</orig> to subterranean veins or stones, as
                        <lb/>Pearls to Zoophytes (that is, a <orig>midle</orig> nature between <orig>animall</orig> and plant)<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and <orig>Corall</orig> to vegetables. The Philosophers stone is indeed like to these stones
                        <lb/>and especially to <orig>Corall</orig>: for as <orig>Corall</orig> <orig>growes</orig> in water, and <orig>drawes</orig> nutriment
                        <lb/>from the earth; <orig>soe</orig> <orig>allso</orig> the <orig>Philosophicall</orig> stone growes in <orig>Mercuriall</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>water, and from it receives whatsoever is earthy, for the augmentation of <orig>it
                        <lb break="no"/>selfe</orig>, the superfluous moisture expiring. A red <orig>colour</orig> is <orig>allso</orig> fixed in <orig>Corall</orig>
                        <lb/>by coagulation, which modern authors call the tincture of <orig>Coralls</orig>, <orig>noe</orig> other
                        <lb break="no"/>wise than as in the <choice><orig>Physicall</orig><reg>Physical</reg></choice> stone, which becomes red in the last coagu
                        <lb break="no"/>lation of it, and appears like the reddest <orig>Corall</orig>, which is the tincture:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>but as <orig>Corall</orig> becomes hard by cold and siccity, <orig>soe</orig> that by heat and sicci
                        <lb break="no"/>ty, which being augmented it likewise dissolves, contrary to the nature of
                        <lb/>other stones, which <orig>doe</orig> indeed dissolve, but <orig>turne</orig> into <orig>glasse</orig>, which thing
                        <lb/>is <choice><orig>noewise</orig><reg>nowise</reg></choice> <orig>agreable</orig> to this: And as <orig>Corall</orig> is <orig>pr√¶pared</orig> into <orig>severall</orig> medi
                        <lb break="no"/>cines of great virtue, <orig>soe</orig> <orig>allso</orig> <orig>hath</orig> the <orig>Philosophicall</orig> <orig>Corall</orig> <choice><orig>transferrd</orig><reg>transferred</reg></choice><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the virtues of all herbs into <orig>itselfe</orig>, <orig>soe</orig> that is alone is able to <orig>performe</orig>
                        <lb/>as much as all the medicines of all vegetables: For the <orig>c√¶lestiall</orig> <orig>Sunne</orig>,
                        <lb/>which <choice><orig>infuseth</orig><reg>infuses</reg></choice> <orig>medicinall</orig> virtue and efficacy into vegetables, contributes
                        <lb/>to this its <orig>Sonne</orig> and <orig>terrestriall</orig> deputy more, than to all others: This is<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>the <orig>Philosophicall</orig> vegetable, <orig>animall</orig>, and <orig>minerall</orig> <orig>Corall</orig>, which <orig>lyes</orig>
                        <lb/>occult in the vast ocean, and is not <orig>knowne</orig>, except it be exposed to the
                        <lb/>eyes and put into the hands of the ignorant: But it must be cut of in
                        <lb/>the water with very great caution, lest it loose its juice and blood, and
                        <lb/>nothing <orig>remayne</orig> but a <orig>terrestriall</orig> chaos without its true <orig>forme</orig>: For
                        <lb/>herein consists all the difficulty of taking <orig>corall</orig>, besides which there is<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>scarce any: The superfluous moisture. I <orig>meane</orig>, which kills the stone,
                        <lb/><orig>unlesse</orig> it be separated, which suffers not the <choice><orig>coralline</orig><reg>coraline</reg></choice> <orig>rednesse</orig> to<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>appear, which <orig>admitts</orig> not coagulation, whilst it is therein<pc>. . . . .</pc><!-- there is a note on the end of this page -->
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
